1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:25,960
 You were saying you've turned a corner in the reading of Hegel.

2
00:00:25,960 --> 00:00:31,960
 Well, okay. So, I mean, I'll give you a little bit of the process just to contextualize.

3
00:00:32,620 --> 00:00:44,100
 But as I told you, I'm writing this thing right now that's going to be probably, I think, like the first chapter or chapter-ishy thing for the book on genealogy and the master-slave and blah, blah, blah.

4
00:00:44,900 --> 00:00:52,720
 And so, of course, I just ended up, I think it's probably just because obviously Hegel's been on my mind, but it's like, you know, I just kind of want to pursue this.

5
00:00:52,720 --> 00:01:01,420
 Well, some people have written about it, right? Like the relationship between Hegel's version of master-slave and Nietzsche's version of master-slave.

6
00:01:02,180 --> 00:01:10,860
 And the thing that became very clear to me reading, and by the way, not a lot of people have written about it, which is something that actually surprised me a great deal.

7
00:01:10,960 --> 00:01:24,240
 Like there's not a ton of stuff there, or maybe there's chunks of chapters somewhere that I didn't find, but in terms of articles or certainly not books, like, I mean, there was a very limited, I mean, like 10 things, like not a whole lot of stuff.

8
00:01:24,240 --> 00:01:25,680
 And so I went through those things.

9
00:01:25,880 --> 00:01:37,520
 And the thing that became pretty clear to me is that Deleuze is the guy who installs this notion of an antagonism between Hegel and Nietzsche.

10
00:01:37,960 --> 00:01:38,040
 Right.

11
00:01:39,700 --> 00:01:55,080
 And so that just, you know, that made me pause a little bit, like, because, like, Walter Kaufman and other, you know, Walter Kaufman is the big Nietzsche translator and also early, you know, sort of existentialist-oriented writer on Nietzsche.

12
00:01:55,640 --> 00:02:04,860
 And he sees, you know, a kind of, and most did prior to Deleuze see, like, hey, these are very similar thinkers.

13
00:02:05,420 --> 00:02:18,020
 And the phrase that I really, really liked to describe Hegel and Nietzsche both was that they're both dialectical monists, which I like that phrase.

14
00:02:18,020 --> 00:02:25,300
 Like, it's a monistic word, but now I would not describe Nietzsche as a dialectical monist, but I'd describe him as an agonistic monist.

15
00:02:25,640 --> 00:02:25,980
 Right.

16
00:02:26,160 --> 00:02:26,440
 Right.

17
00:02:26,520 --> 00:02:33,740
 So it's, they're not terribly far afield from that agonistic or dialectical distinction.

18
00:02:33,900 --> 00:02:47,220
 So in any case, it's like, Deleuze's book is that Nietzsche and philosophy, 1962, like, that's the moment where this argument began of, like, you know, the Deleuzians don't like Hegel or whatever.

19
00:02:47,500 --> 00:02:47,780
 Right.

20
00:02:47,780 --> 00:02:55,280
 And I also remembered from my last reading, the last time that I read Nietzsche and philosophy, which I can't remember, but it's not too long ago.

21
00:02:56,520 --> 00:02:58,560
 That I was really, I really accentuated.

22
00:02:58,680 --> 00:02:59,900
 Didn't we do it this summer?

23
00:02:59,960 --> 00:03:00,740
 Did we do it this summer?

24
00:03:01,660 --> 00:03:01,820
 Yeah.

25
00:03:01,920 --> 00:03:03,580
 We did that chapter, yeah.

26
00:03:03,680 --> 00:03:04,440
 The last chapter.

27
00:03:04,480 --> 00:03:04,980
 Right, right.

28
00:03:05,360 --> 00:03:16,640
 So in that last chapter, I mean, and something that I kind of emphasized a lot in my reading was that he both establishes them as opposites and undercuts the establishing of opposition.

29
00:03:16,640 --> 00:03:24,060
 Right, like, and that's the part that is totally missing from the reception, the undercutting of the opposition.

30
00:03:24,740 --> 00:03:32,440
 So, because, I mean, Deleuze says very, very clearly, like, from the perspective of dialectics, Hegel and Nietzsche are opposites.

31
00:03:32,860 --> 00:03:35,440
 But from the perspective of Nietzsche, they're just different.

32
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:36,280
 Right.

33
00:03:36,280 --> 00:03:42,880
 I mean, you know, in other words, that opposition is the slave way of thinking, you know, for Deleuze.

34
00:03:43,280 --> 00:03:50,260
 So, the idea that Deleuze simply installs an opposition between Hegel, which is the sort of received story.

35
00:03:50,380 --> 00:03:51,120
 Deleuze is the guy.

36
00:03:51,220 --> 00:03:52,120
 He installs an opposition.

37
00:03:52,280 --> 00:03:54,840
 But that's way, way too simplistic.

38
00:03:54,840 --> 00:04:02,340
 And it really just kind of got me, like, well, I would say the easiest way of saying it is I think I started reading Hegel a little more sympathetically.

39
00:04:02,840 --> 00:04:03,040
 Yeah.

40
00:04:03,760 --> 00:04:07,260
 And, like I said, a little bit less suspiciously.

41
00:04:07,980 --> 00:04:13,580
 I still have, I don't think that I've lost the reservations that I've had as we've talked throughout.

42
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,720
 But I really see what he's doing now.

43
00:04:17,440 --> 00:04:20,360
 Like, I really see it as committed to process thinking.

44
00:04:20,680 --> 00:04:26,280
 You know, and that's all, and the section that we read for today is just so clear on that.

45
00:04:26,360 --> 00:04:30,920
 Like, his beef with math is entirely that there's no process.

46
00:04:31,380 --> 00:04:31,560
 Right.

47
00:04:31,600 --> 00:04:31,820
 Right.

48
00:04:32,020 --> 00:04:34,500
 It's concerned with sort of results and proof, you know.

49
00:04:34,880 --> 00:04:38,440
 And it just eliminates the movement of the thing.

50
00:04:38,440 --> 00:04:46,720
 Now, again, I still have these issues with, like, its own and the necessity of the movement coming from inside itself and the metaphorics of that.

51
00:04:47,180 --> 00:04:52,500
 But I do think that, you know, following Zizek, it's also been reading the Malibu and Zizek.

52
00:04:54,140 --> 00:04:59,060
 But there are ways of undermining, I mean, and it's not hard.

53
00:04:59,180 --> 00:05:02,280
 Or there are ways of reading Hegel against the grain in that sense.

54
00:05:02,380 --> 00:05:06,820
 And it's not difficult to do when he says, you know, the movement comes from within itself.

55
00:05:06,820 --> 00:05:17,440
 It's easy to show how that's not really within itself, that the within itself is already a sort of result of an extrinsic or external force.

56
00:05:18,420 --> 00:05:31,480
 So, nevertheless, like, the result for me has simply been, like, you know, I just feel I'm reading it way more sympathetically than I was over the last, you know, over the summer when we were doing the majority of these videos.

57
00:05:31,660 --> 00:05:44,320
 Well, yeah, the critique of math in this section, parts of it, maybe just because I've been trying to sort of synthesize the Deleuzian and the Hegelian positions, if you want to call them that.

58
00:05:44,580 --> 00:06:00,140
 But I thought there were moments where Hegel's focus on contingency and becoming, even if the dynamics of that becoming are different and even crucially different from Deleuz's, there were portions where it's like, that could have been a Deleuz's sentence here and there.

59
00:06:00,180 --> 00:06:00,460
 Yeah, I agree.

60
00:06:00,460 --> 00:06:07,140
 With the way he's confronting the representationalism that's sort of inherent to math.

61
00:06:07,660 --> 00:06:09,140
 And Kant's version.

62
00:06:09,140 --> 00:06:13,820
 And then Kant, and then offering the alternative in its nation form there.

63
00:06:14,680 --> 00:06:19,680
 I don't know, it didn't read to me as, like, anti-Deleuz in any way.

64
00:06:19,780 --> 00:06:20,280
 Yeah, no.

65
00:06:20,700 --> 00:06:20,860
 Yeah.

66
00:06:20,920 --> 00:06:21,120
 No.

67
00:06:21,880 --> 00:06:26,920
 I think you can read him generously, too, on the sort of inside-outside distinction as well.

68
00:06:26,920 --> 00:06:39,200
 Because, I mean, the problem with math for him is that it creates a bunch of equations, but no particular, like, because an equation is always a resting place, there is nothing about that dynamic.

69
00:06:39,380 --> 00:06:45,860
 There's no essential inequality or difference that leads to its self-transformation.

70
00:06:46,200 --> 00:06:54,640
 And so, you know, I don't think that you need to read a stark binary between the inside and the outside to get at the kind of imminent self-overcoming that he's talking about.

71
00:06:54,640 --> 00:07:02,980
 Which is to say, like, which is to say that there cannot be an inside, a pure inside at all, because that would be an equation.

72
00:07:03,180 --> 00:07:13,060
 Ultimately, it is math that creates both the pure inside as the equation and then the pure outside that has to put one equation in relationship to another one.

73
00:07:13,740 --> 00:07:14,000
 Right, yeah.

74
00:07:14,780 --> 00:07:24,580
 And, I mean, you bring this, you just brought this up, but that was most striking to me was Hegel on equality sounds just like Nietzsche on equality.

75
00:07:25,420 --> 00:07:34,400
 Right, I mean, they really, like, these concepts, they're static concepts, they don't, or rather they're not concepts for Hegel because that would be, you know, they're not notions.

76
00:07:34,740 --> 00:07:34,940
 But, yeah.

77
00:07:35,100 --> 00:07:43,200
 But, nevertheless, like, it's their antagonism or frustration with the idea of equality, they both share it.

78
00:07:43,260 --> 00:07:51,060
 Now, there's a huge difference because, for Hegel, it has to get to opposition in order for it to be not equality.

79
00:07:51,560 --> 00:07:53,280
 And that's not true for Nietzsche, right?

80
00:07:53,440 --> 00:08:01,000
 Like, so, in other words, that's where difference multiplicity, I still think, is the non-systematic response to this.

81
00:08:01,100 --> 00:08:08,880
 But, still, in terms of the thinking of equality, they both are deeply skeptical of it as a founding concept for math.

82
00:08:13,880 --> 00:08:24,240
 I'm on 46, paragraph 46, towards the bottom, and, yeah, again, we have the slightly different translations.

83
00:08:25,440 --> 00:08:44,300
 But, he goes, the principle of magnitude, or the principle of the conceptless difference, and the principle of equality, or that of abstract, lifeless unity, are incapable of dealing with that pure restlessness of life and its absolute difference.

84
00:08:44,300 --> 00:09:00,140
 And, to me, again, like, he complicates it and he gets into the more phenomenological determinations later, but that, the pure restlessness of life and its absolute difference, that, to me, sounds like a Nietzschean or a Deleuzian sentiment there.

85
00:09:00,160 --> 00:09:00,460
 Totally.

86
00:09:00,740 --> 00:09:03,740
 Like, you could have cut that right out of either of them.

87
00:09:03,900 --> 00:09:21,960
 And, that basic critique of representationalism there, to me, is, like, I don't know, it just seems directly related to Deleuz's critique of the same thing, in both what is philosophy and, kind of, in the Nietzsche and philosophy book, as well.

88
00:09:22,760 --> 00:09:32,440
 Yeah, I mean, you know, what's translated here is the notion is the concept, right, I mean, if that's the big riff, right, like, that's the word that we would normally use.

89
00:09:32,440 --> 00:09:41,920
 I mean, I think that you're spot on, right, it's the reason there, that the concept in early, in difference in repetition, the concept is bad, right, the concept is the form of representation.

90
00:09:42,400 --> 00:09:58,300
 But, what is philosophy, I think that you're spot on, like, that's where the concept is the sort of self, not, again, you have to be careful with all these words, but these self-moving, self-transformative entity, you know, and that's what it sounds like here.

91
00:09:58,300 --> 00:10:06,020
 I mean, it's, like, what is philosophy's, thinking of the concept, is frickin' Hegel's concept of the concept.

92
00:10:06,520 --> 00:10:19,760
 Exactly, well, the concept in Hegel here is attentive to that difference, whereas in math, the lifeless concept is just merely applied to life, it's a lifeless unity, right, so those delineations between,

93
00:10:20,300 --> 00:10:30,480
 now, I don't know how useful it is, sorry, I might be jumping ahead a little bit, but, to, like, name people, we've done, we've tried to do this a few times, like, is Descartes a target here?

94
00:10:30,880 --> 00:10:34,880
 Like, is rationalism sort of a name for this mathematical thinking?

95
00:10:35,280 --> 00:10:40,060
 I mean, it doesn't really matter, because I know that he goes through all these targets in the preface.

96
00:10:40,600 --> 00:10:49,060
 He kind of starts with empiricism, I think, moves through Spinoza, who's a weird, I don't even really know how to label him, and now we're on math.

97
00:10:49,700 --> 00:10:55,160
 And I'm just, I was wondering, we don't have to answer this right now, but, like, how each of those targets relate to each other?

98
00:10:55,360 --> 00:11:04,540
 Because you usually think of empiricism as being the opposite, or a completely different approach from math, right?

99
00:11:04,640 --> 00:11:08,140
 Or, like, from rationalism, at least from their inception.

100
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:10,740
 But, uh, he seems to...

101
00:11:10,740 --> 00:11:15,540
 You'd be moving back in time to go to Descartes, maybe Leibniz would be a little bit...

102
00:11:15,540 --> 00:11:19,680
 Right, right. Well, I guess, and Kant is explicitly named soon after this.

103
00:11:19,840 --> 00:11:20,100
 Yeah.

104
00:11:20,400 --> 00:11:36,520
 So, um, but it was just, it was just interesting to me, because I thought about this in a seminar paper a while ago, and I think probably a bunch of people have written this, but, like, the opposition between the empiricist movement and the rationalist movement during that time period, they were directly opposed to each other, right?

105
00:11:36,940 --> 00:11:39,880
 And one of them is explicitly inductive, right?

106
00:11:40,480 --> 00:11:57,560
 Empiricism is the sort of more humble approach, right, where you don't start with a theory, you start with observation and experimentation and then derive a theory from that, whereas Descartes' rationalism applies a theory first and then, you know, observes matter after that.

107
00:11:57,780 --> 00:12:08,820
 But to me, it's like they're both confronting and kind of suppressing the same, the problem that Hegel's trying to articulate, which is the movement of conceptuality itself.

108
00:12:09,120 --> 00:12:12,600
 Like, that's what they're both alighting in those paradoxes.

109
00:12:12,600 --> 00:12:14,760
 Because they're both looking for propositional truth, right?

110
00:12:14,780 --> 00:12:15,300
 Right, right.

111
00:12:16,080 --> 00:12:16,540
 Yeah, exactly.

112
00:12:16,680 --> 00:12:16,840
 Yeah.

113
00:12:18,140 --> 00:12:30,680
 I was just going to say, John, I wanted to speak a little bit to your hesitancy on the inside-outside dichotomy, where you're like, you have to be careful about this whole self-moving thing.

114
00:12:30,680 --> 00:12:38,240
 And I think there's maybe a helpful way of nuancing between two notions of the inside or of imminence, right?

115
00:12:38,280 --> 00:12:56,520
 Because, you know, if we're thinking in the Aristotelian tradition or, like, the Platonic tradition of, like, why something that is self-moving is somehow simply better than things that are not moving, it's because there is, like, that self-moving becomes a property of a stabilized thing, right?

116
00:12:56,520 --> 00:13:12,220
 So, you know, the self-moving thing, like the soul or whatever else, that is, it maintains its integrity through its movement, right?

117
00:13:12,340 --> 00:13:18,420
 And part of, and it's equally important that it self-moves and that it maintains its integrity as it moves.

118
00:13:18,420 --> 00:13:29,840
 But the second notion of self-movement, like, takes on a notion of the self that is already punctured, that is already sort of folded between the inside and the outside.

119
00:13:29,840 --> 00:13:49,760
 So for that self-movement, it is not just the displacement of something that has, that maintains its integrity, but it is reconstituted, its movement is its own reconstitution, which means that it is already opened up to the outside.

120
00:13:49,760 --> 00:14:17,460
 And I think that the problem, the beef that Hegel has here, I think I'm just now re-articulating what I said before, but the problem that Hegel has with the mathematical or propositional truth to begin with is that because it's closed off, because it deals with, like, it does maintain its integrity, it can't self-transform, right?

121
00:14:17,460 --> 00:14:24,620
 It can't have no self-movement, because self-movement would necessarily lead to its own transformation.

122
00:14:24,840 --> 00:14:27,320
 It is too impregnable, as it were.

123
00:14:27,840 --> 00:14:27,960
 Right.

124
00:14:28,640 --> 00:14:33,040
 Well, there's no room for the self in this form of mathematics, right?

125
00:14:33,400 --> 00:14:40,300
 There's not even, like, it almost has to be removed for that kind of thinking to work.

126
00:14:40,300 --> 00:14:54,500
 And this is something that I keep running up against when I try to think about both, like, traditional Newtonian physics and math and stuff like this, because the issue with math is not math in itself, like, or its function.

127
00:14:54,640 --> 00:14:56,460
 Like, it works, right?

128
00:14:56,740 --> 00:14:59,600
 Like, it has functions in the world, and it works.

129
00:14:59,720 --> 00:15:01,620
 And Newtonian physics is the same thing.

130
00:15:01,680 --> 00:15:08,020
 I mean, you can build stuff with that kind of non-theoretical or non-quantum version of physics.

131
00:15:08,020 --> 00:15:17,060
 The issue seems to be, maybe this is reductive, but for Hegel is that it doesn't simply rest at its function, right?

132
00:15:17,100 --> 00:15:23,320
 So it's functional, it works in the world to an extent, but it wants to also contain truth about the world.

133
00:15:23,840 --> 00:15:27,240
 Yeah, it's the question of math status.

134
00:15:27,480 --> 00:15:27,880
 Right, right.

135
00:15:27,940 --> 00:15:36,680
 So when it becomes a philosophy, which it always already was, that's when it becomes problematic, because it's, like, there's an arrogance to it.

136
00:15:37,740 --> 00:15:53,140
 And so when that kind of representationalist thinking infiltrates all thinking to some extent, right, like, in terms of Heidegger's critique of, like, humanism and representationalism, that's when you encounter, like, political and ethical problems, right?

137
00:15:53,820 --> 00:16:02,820
 I would even push that further, that Hegel has a problem with the functional notion of mathematics as well, precisely because math can't function, right?

138
00:16:02,980 --> 00:16:05,660
 Math can only represent itself.

139
00:16:05,960 --> 00:16:13,720
 It only, like, you know, take whatever mathematical formula, and it only takes itself as its object.

140
00:16:13,720 --> 00:16:25,640
 That to then take a mathematical formula, like, a series of mathematical formulas and apply it to a ravine where I want to build the bridge is now a non-mathematical application of mathematical equations.

141
00:16:25,640 --> 00:16:28,300
 Because, like, you know, this is what he's going on.

142
00:16:29,120 --> 00:16:37,520
 Whenever he's talking about magnitude and space and times, like, look, math doesn't take the world as its object.

143
00:16:37,520 --> 00:16:46,620
 It takes an abstracted notion of time and space and then differentiates orders of magnitude within that, right?

144
00:16:46,640 --> 00:16:54,520
 And so that's why, like, if you actually were able to set math out into the world, it would undo itself and become something else.

145
00:16:54,800 --> 00:17:01,440
 The math, this is what I mean by the self, not, like, a subjective human psyche, but, like, the self-same proposition.

146
00:17:01,440 --> 00:17:08,640
 You know, E equals mc squared is a self-contained entity that cannot refer to anything beyond itself.

147
00:17:09,140 --> 00:17:09,520
 Right.

148
00:17:09,860 --> 00:17:15,140
 Well, I guess I'm conflating, like, math in itself and then in its practical application.

149
00:17:15,360 --> 00:17:24,440
 I suppose I was taking for granted that math is always sort of, like, it's loosely – because with physics, like, right, you're applying theorems,

150
00:17:24,440 --> 00:17:32,160
 but there's also a lot of experimentation and observation that accounts for that contingency that math can't account for, right?

151
00:17:32,320 --> 00:17:41,000
 So there's always the combination in engineering whatever with the, like, the sort of abstract a priori theorems

152
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:45,360
 and then their practical application and then working them out in physical space.

153
00:17:45,720 --> 00:17:46,320
 Does that make any sense?

154
00:17:46,460 --> 00:17:51,220
 So when I was saying, like, that math works, I think I was just, like, taking for granted that it's always, like,

155
00:17:51,220 --> 00:17:55,500
 sort of massaged in a way in its practical application.

156
00:17:56,060 --> 00:18:00,400
 Well, and he says – there's one point where he makes a comment like that is that, you know,

157
00:18:00,460 --> 00:18:03,880
 you could even add in a little bit of contingency and get something better.

158
00:18:05,380 --> 00:18:07,760
 This method – and he's talking here about math.

159
00:18:07,800 --> 00:18:09,920
 This is in paragraph 48.

160
00:18:10,600 --> 00:18:13,500
 You don't have to go to it because it's just an incidental comment.

161
00:18:13,840 --> 00:18:16,480
 But it's peculiar to mathematics, yada, yada.

162
00:18:16,480 --> 00:18:21,060
 This method in a looser form, i.e. more blended with the arbitrary and the accidental,

163
00:18:21,320 --> 00:18:27,580
 may retain its place as in conversation or in a piece of historical knowledge designed rather to satisfy curiosity

164
00:18:27,580 --> 00:18:30,640
 than to produce knowledge, which is what a preface amounts to, right?

165
00:18:30,700 --> 00:18:34,600
 Like, in other words, like, you could – you can throw some contingency into mathematics

166
00:18:34,600 --> 00:18:38,880
 and have it be more – have it be functional in the terms that we're talking about.

167
00:18:39,320 --> 00:18:47,040
 Do you guys know if someone's written a book on math and philosophy?

168
00:18:47,680 --> 00:18:49,540
 Like, you know, like –

169
00:18:49,540 --> 00:18:50,300
 Oh, there's a whole era.

170
00:18:50,960 --> 00:18:55,820
 Not an expert book, but, I mean, like an introduction because it just seems to me like the –

171
00:18:55,820 --> 00:18:59,700
 I mean, it's been a troubled relationship since Plato, right?

172
00:18:59,840 --> 00:19:07,220
 Like, I mean, we had the slave drawing the diagram in the sand, you know, that that relationship is one.

173
00:19:07,340 --> 00:19:14,260
 I mean, here it's being made explicit, but, I mean – and it is this idea of the claim to universality, right?

174
00:19:14,260 --> 00:19:24,600
 Like, that math reveals something called truths that are absolute and everywhere, like 180 degrees in a triangle, you know?

175
00:19:24,760 --> 00:19:26,580
 I mean, those sorts of things.

176
00:19:26,840 --> 00:19:32,780
 And that has often, and in many places, been the aspiration of philosophy.

177
00:19:33,500 --> 00:19:34,060
 Right.

178
00:19:34,220 --> 00:19:40,320
 Is to reveal those always and for everywhere truths for some philosophers.

179
00:19:40,540 --> 00:19:52,100
 Now, again, I mean, to me, what you were saying about inside, outside in the previous part of the conversation, Nathaniel, is, like, would be so much easier if you just added in perspectivism.

180
00:19:52,800 --> 00:19:58,900
 You know, if you just said, like, from the perspective of, you know, the entity, it looks like it's self-moved.

181
00:19:59,020 --> 00:20:01,980
 From the perspective of the exterior, it looks – you know what I mean?

182
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:10,160
 Like, if you just added in different – that's what Nietzsche does, is that it's just – and so, you know, truth is not – I mean, in this sense, truth.

183
00:20:10,160 --> 00:20:34,540
 This is where – I mean, interestingly enough, while the thinking might have lots of overlap, this is a thinking that is still totally dedicated to truth in ways that Nietzsche's is a total questioning of the viability of truth or the usefulness or the – you know, and that's a major – because to me, I still think that Deleuze's – I mean, I'm still invested in Deleuze's interest.

184
00:20:34,540 --> 00:20:40,660
 Where it's like, look, there's something about the tone or, in my terms of style, that negation brings with it.

185
00:20:41,200 --> 00:20:55,360
 And I think that's getting kind of close to what that tone is here, is that systematic drive towards truth is still very much a part of this discourse, even if the thinking has very similar contents.

186
00:20:56,540 --> 00:20:56,840
 You know?

187
00:20:57,420 --> 00:20:57,700
 Right, right.

188
00:20:58,300 --> 00:20:59,860
 For Nietzsche, there's no – there's no truth.

189
00:20:59,940 --> 00:21:01,580
 Like, we're not going to get a better understanding.

190
00:21:01,640 --> 00:21:10,160
 It's not like mathematical knowledge is lesser – I mean, for Hegel, mathematical knowledge is lesser knowledge for all of the reasons that we've been talking about.

191
00:21:10,540 --> 00:21:20,040
 You know, and it does not reach the level of philosophical knowledge because it's not – it's not truth in the, you know, important way.

192
00:21:20,400 --> 00:21:20,620
 Right.

193
00:21:20,820 --> 00:21:28,300
 Well, it doesn't – I mean, in really simple terms, it just doesn't incorporate the movement of the concept into the system.

194
00:21:28,880 --> 00:21:39,400
 And so the really common, easy critique of math that any, like, eighth grader could ascertain is here, where it's like math is too abstract.

195
00:21:39,680 --> 00:21:41,080
 Like, I don't know what to do with it.

196
00:21:41,140 --> 00:21:43,320
 It doesn't seem to be attached to the world in any way.

197
00:21:43,400 --> 00:21:44,620
 So you do an equation.

198
00:21:44,760 --> 00:21:47,900
 You're like, how does this relate to life in any real way?

199
00:21:47,900 --> 00:21:59,460
 You see that here, but the slightly more important twist, I think, is Hegel's actually saying it's not only too abstract, it's also not abstract enough.

200
00:21:59,480 --> 00:22:00,360
 Not abstract enough.

201
00:22:00,360 --> 00:22:04,180
 In the sense that it's not attentive to its movement of abstraction.

202
00:22:04,180 --> 00:22:17,200
 So that's when you take the step from the understanding, which is that violent, abstracting force, which is the motor of mathematics or that version of rationalism.

203
00:22:17,560 --> 00:22:25,700
 And then you start – it's just a simple shift in perspective where you start, like, just recognizing that movement.

204
00:22:26,280 --> 00:22:31,680
 And so you incorporate that movement into the system as opposed to just simply suppressing it.

205
00:22:32,780 --> 00:22:32,980
 Right.

206
00:22:33,140 --> 00:22:35,080
 Which I think is what he's calling for, yeah.

207
00:22:35,080 --> 00:22:45,780
 I want to ask you guys – I mean, one of the big questions that I have in this passage – like, I don't know if this goes too far into 37 – page 37, sorry, like, paragraph 59.

208
00:22:46,200 --> 00:22:48,040
 But, well, there's some of it earlier.

209
00:22:49,140 --> 00:23:02,100
 The notion of the – okay, so, like, if we look at, for instance, paragraph 53, section 53,

210
00:23:02,100 --> 00:23:20,200
 which for us is divided into two really big, long paragraphs, the second one beginning Nathaniel on page 32 there, with even when the specific determinants – say one like Magnus, is it self-concrete or real – the understanding degrades it into something lifeless.

211
00:23:21,040 --> 00:23:31,800
 So, and what I'm raising into question here is the function of the understanding, because in this passage, the understanding seems like it's the thing that rigidifies, right?

212
00:23:31,800 --> 00:23:37,500
 Which I read is like, okay, so here's what kind of understanding as a faculty, right?

213
00:23:37,680 --> 00:23:43,480
 As a faculty, it's a faculty that suppresses movement, right?

214
00:23:43,560 --> 00:23:45,340
 That sort of isolates out.

215
00:23:45,460 --> 00:23:48,060
 So, the understanding degrades it into something lifeless.

216
00:23:48,460 --> 00:23:56,620
 And yet in other places, I feel like the understanding is precisely the thing that's necessary to, you know, to get at the notion.

217
00:23:56,960 --> 00:24:01,860
 And so, I just found this – it was just a question, you know, like a little bit above that.

218
00:24:01,920 --> 00:24:08,140
 The understanding in its pigeonholing process keeps the necessity and the notion of the content to itself, right?

219
00:24:08,200 --> 00:24:13,560
 So, the understanding is that is sort of what I would call like that which taxonomizes, right?

220
00:24:13,560 --> 00:24:30,280
 Like that which puts things into a grid and which, again, is a necessary part of the process of recognizing that there is a grid and that one is gridifying, you know, things.

221
00:24:30,800 --> 00:24:39,060
 So, I mean, maybe I'm answering my own question, I guess, is that – but it's – so at moments, the understanding seems like it's this delimiting force.

222
00:24:39,500 --> 00:24:43,700
 And then other moments, it seems like it's this undelimiting force.

223
00:24:43,860 --> 00:24:46,740
 It's that which is putting things into motion, I guess.

224
00:24:47,440 --> 00:24:48,700
 So, that was just a question.

225
00:24:49,460 --> 00:24:52,540
 But it seems there seems to be two movements of understanding.

226
00:24:52,700 --> 00:24:55,320
 And this – I mean, this seems to be pretty consistent for a while.

227
00:24:55,320 --> 00:25:04,580
 And what we just read today, for today, think about when he's talking about the triangle and he's like, look, the first movement of the understanding –

228
00:25:04,580 --> 00:25:13,220
 you know, like you start with the simplicity – to bring this back out to the general more – to the preface more generally.

229
00:25:13,220 --> 00:25:27,980
 He always begins with one version of the simplicity that then needs to be differentiated and taxonomized and then brought back to a second simplicity, right?

230
00:25:28,480 --> 00:25:35,040
 And he sort of localizes that example with the triangles, understanding, you know, the Euclidean relationships of the right triangle.

231
00:25:35,040 --> 00:25:41,100
 It's like that first motion of the understanding breaks it up into these discrete parts.

232
00:25:41,220 --> 00:25:48,900
 And those parts do not refer to the triangle but refer to other figures like, you know, a right angle and squares and whatever else.

233
00:25:49,020 --> 00:26:07,080
 And then it's only once you're able to put those parts back together, which is the second movement of understanding, that you have the notion of the right triangle as a living concept, as a living truth.

234
00:26:09,240 --> 00:26:17,880
 And this is before he goes into just wholesale critiquing mathematics.

235
00:26:18,620 --> 00:26:30,740
 And so when I read a sentence like that, you know, that the understanding degrades it into something lifeless, I immediately think that this is that first movement of the understanding,

236
00:26:30,740 --> 00:26:43,000
 which has to take the concept like magnetism and then it has to separate it from everything else in order to be able to figure out the other component parts before it gets put all back together again into a second simplicity.

237
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:51,460
 Yeah, and this is one of the tricky things for me, and it's not explicitly laid out in this section, I don't think,

238
00:26:51,460 --> 00:26:59,680
 but the understanding, sort of like Foucault's notion of power, it's only functional if it's basically unnoticed.

239
00:27:00,160 --> 00:27:09,500
 So like, sort of with sense certainty, right, like, in order to perceive your world and identify objects and identify yourself within the world,

240
00:27:09,760 --> 00:27:17,920
 that process of sensuality, I don't even know what to call it, sensuality, sense certainty, has to be masked somehow.

241
00:27:18,020 --> 00:27:23,400
 So it has to sort of run smoothly, and you can't be consciously aware of it.

242
00:27:23,720 --> 00:27:29,920
 That, to me, is part and parcel of also the function of the understanding, if you can even separate that,

243
00:27:30,060 --> 00:27:32,400
 from sense certainty.

244
00:27:32,400 --> 00:27:42,400
 So, the weird thing for me is that, for Hegel, like you were just saying, John, like, the understanding is both, like, sort of the enemy and the savior.

245
00:27:42,400 --> 00:27:45,400
 Yeah, which is appropriate, I mean, that's appropriate.

246
00:27:45,400 --> 00:27:53,660
 Right, and you have to hold both of those kind of in mind, I mean, that's kind of the movement of the dialectic, where, previously in the preface he says,

247
00:27:53,660 --> 00:27:56,880
 the understanding is like the most spectacular feat of humanity.

248
00:27:56,880 --> 00:27:57,200
 That's right.

249
00:27:57,360 --> 00:28:01,300
 That's what allows us to taxonomize and whatever, appropriate the world and all that.

250
00:28:01,660 --> 00:28:03,560
 But here, it's the explicit enemy.

251
00:28:04,000 --> 00:28:14,640
 You have to sublate it somehow, not for a higher form of thinking, but you simply have to take it into account, which is precisely what it doesn't allow.

252
00:28:14,960 --> 00:28:17,680
 The understanding doesn't allow you to take it into account.

253
00:28:18,340 --> 00:28:25,780
 So, how do we get to, like, the next step, which is reason or self-consciousness, which is, like, the good thing for Hegel?

254
00:28:25,820 --> 00:28:31,160
 It's still a little confusing for me, but I don't know.

255
00:28:31,160 --> 00:28:45,720
 No, I think you're right, and I think, you know, in that sense it reads, you know, it reads more like Nietzsche, where Nietzsche doesn't mark his contradictions and doesn't say a different aspect of the understanding, does it?

256
00:28:45,720 --> 00:28:59,120
 He just, you know, like, he leaves that to the reader to either get it wrong or whatever, but it's like, you know, eight pages later after you said this, you know, this thing is noble, you're like, nobility is for morons, right?

257
00:28:59,120 --> 00:29:28,700
 It's like, and as we know, and as is confirmed in my rereading of, you know, the scholarship linking the two, everybody thinks that Nietzsche has said that the noble is good, I don't mean that in the good, bad, good, evil, but, like, the noble is better than the slave, and it's like, holy fuck, how can you read that and just ignore the passages where he says, this is what made man interesting, man would have been too stupid of a species without, you know, like, but they do, right?

258
00:29:28,700 --> 00:29:38,020
 Like, they just ignore or miss those places where it's like, look, the noble is not the good guy here, not simply the good guy, right?

259
00:29:38,020 --> 00:29:39,220
 Well, there's so much more nuance.

260
00:29:39,220 --> 00:29:40,160
 So that's where they're similar.

261
00:29:40,420 --> 00:29:42,860
 Yeah, there's so much more nuance in all of these thinkers.

262
00:29:43,180 --> 00:29:57,300
 Like, the issue for me that I've, after this, we did, like, you know, six, seven of these podcasts, I was just trying to basically reconcile some of these positions with each other, because nobody seems to want to do that.

263
00:29:57,660 --> 00:30:09,040
 Like, I mean, Deleuze was super confrontational against Hegel, which I get sort of served its purpose, and then all of the followers of each of these movements are so polemical against the different versions of this.

264
00:30:09,040 --> 00:30:19,920
 Like, you get, they've labeled it affirmationism, which is sort of a jibe, usually, at, like, Deleuze and Nietzsche, and then you have the dialecticians, or the people on team negation.

265
00:30:19,920 --> 00:30:26,100
 And it's like, I don't think any of these thinkers worked in those categories that strictly.

266
00:30:26,840 --> 00:30:34,660
 Or at least, their conceptual delineations offer way more than simply, I'm team affirmation.

267
00:30:47,380 --> 00:30:52,980
 I mean, my whole thing, in terms of the Deleuze book, was, like, with active force, like, there's no such thing as active force.

268
00:30:53,460 --> 00:30:55,680
 That's my line on reading the thing.

269
00:30:55,920 --> 00:30:56,540
 There can't be.

270
00:30:56,640 --> 00:30:58,040
 Otherwise, it doesn't make sense.

271
00:30:58,360 --> 00:30:59,980
 And I would say the same thing about affirmation.

272
00:31:00,080 --> 00:31:01,380
 There's no such thing as affirmation.

273
00:31:01,500 --> 00:31:04,400
 It's not a thing that is distinct from negation.

274
00:31:04,540 --> 00:31:05,520
 Like, there can't be.

275
00:31:05,860 --> 00:31:10,560
 Otherwise, that is the negated version of affirmation that makes it into a team process.

276
00:31:10,560 --> 00:31:16,660
 But, I mean, the thing that's frustrating for me is, like, this has been a problem for me for a long time.

277
00:31:17,100 --> 00:31:24,600
 And, obviously, in my book, I mean, if you just, even a cursory reading of it would say, look, he doesn't hate negation.

278
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:27,620
 He's just interested in something else.

279
00:31:28,380 --> 00:31:30,120
 And that's how I felt about it.

280
00:31:30,320 --> 00:31:31,820
 And I had a difficult time.

281
00:31:31,920 --> 00:31:33,760
 I mean, that was 20 years ago, for fuck's sake.

282
00:31:33,880 --> 00:31:42,000
 Like, negotiating, like, trying to figure out how to articulate what I'm doing that's not the same as negation, but neither is it simply different from it.

283
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:43,240
 Like, I had a hard time with that.

284
00:31:43,300 --> 00:31:46,340
 There's long passages in that book where I struggle with it.

285
00:31:46,420 --> 00:31:48,060
 And I'm fucking still struggling with it.

286
00:31:48,300 --> 00:31:48,440
 Right?

287
00:31:48,440 --> 00:31:50,180
 We're still, we're doing this thing.

288
00:31:50,240 --> 00:31:55,720
 So this idea that I'm team affirmation is just like, that's just, that's just lazy.

289
00:31:56,100 --> 00:31:56,620
 No, it's silly.

290
00:31:56,620 --> 00:31:57,160
 It's silly.

291
00:31:57,420 --> 00:31:57,920
 It's silly.

292
00:31:58,080 --> 00:32:03,340
 But you can see why people are, like, willing to make those jumps.

293
00:32:03,340 --> 00:32:14,720
 Not because of your work lends it to that, but because there are these camps, like, including your work, but, like, besides that, with Barad and people out in, like, other fields.

294
00:32:15,260 --> 00:32:18,980
 People latch on to these kind of movements, and it's easy for them.

295
00:32:19,260 --> 00:32:26,140
 So, like, let's say negation has been kind of thrown to the side for the past decade or something, or maybe even two decades.

296
00:32:26,520 --> 00:32:29,140
 Now, it's time to save negation.

297
00:32:29,140 --> 00:32:31,020
 And this is what Benjamin Noyes does.

298
00:32:31,320 --> 00:32:34,000
 It's like, negation is actually the key to an ethical world.

299
00:32:34,260 --> 00:32:36,220
 And it's like, man, did you read Hegel?

300
00:32:36,280 --> 00:32:37,500
 Did you ever actually read Hegel?

301
00:32:37,800 --> 00:32:39,980
 Because I don't think that was ever explicit.

302
00:32:39,980 --> 00:32:51,140
 That's where, see, that's where I would argue, if you want to talk about the movement of historical change, it looks and smells like a dialectic that doesn't sublate at all, right?

303
00:32:51,180 --> 00:32:53,360
 Like, there's no off-haben element to it.

304
00:32:53,380 --> 00:32:59,160
 It's just like, yes, no, yes, no, yes, no, yes, no, yes, no.

305
00:32:59,420 --> 00:33:01,160
 You're like, what the fuck?

306
00:33:03,260 --> 00:33:09,180
 So that's the change we get in history is just like, yes, no, no, yes, yes, no.

307
00:33:09,980 --> 00:33:12,000
 It's just a lot of chaos, you know?

308
00:33:12,060 --> 00:33:15,380
 Yeah, well, it's just, but it's just a non-engagement, right?

309
00:33:15,420 --> 00:33:26,860
 It's not, there's, I mean, if, the problem is there's not enough off-habening, which would be raising it and, you know, maintaining the distinctions and suspending the differences between them.

310
00:33:26,960 --> 00:33:29,640
 It's like, oh, like in the actual discourse, yeah, too.

311
00:33:29,800 --> 00:33:31,960
 Right, like, where's the fucking off-haben?

312
00:33:32,280 --> 00:33:35,000
 Like, I'm waiting for some off-habens to happen.

313
00:33:35,200 --> 00:33:38,120
 It just seems like it's, yes, no, yes, no.

314
00:33:39,080 --> 00:33:42,340
 It doesn't seem like we're able to do many off-habens in scholarship.

315
00:33:43,080 --> 00:33:43,520
 Right.

316
00:33:43,520 --> 00:33:45,080
 It's pretty tough, yeah.

317
00:33:45,480 --> 00:33:53,220
 So I just, in the History of Rhetoric class, I just gave a midterm, and one of the essay questions was basically like,

318
00:33:53,780 --> 00:34:11,240
 and all, so I had them read Gorgias' Encomium of Helen, Plato's Gorgias, Augustine's De Magistro, and the, like, chunks of Book 4 on Christian Doctrine, and then chunks of Bacon's on the Advancement of Learning, and the Novum Organum.

319
00:34:11,780 --> 00:34:32,100
 Like, one of the questions, like, one of the consistent themes that we find in all of these texts, or most of these texts, is a sort of an anxiety about a supposedly, like, world of falsity or appearance or, like, surface simulacrum, and then the sort of the true world that it hides.

320
00:34:32,100 --> 00:34:57,560
 And we get these in a number of figures, like, you know, the semblance art distinction that Plato makes, or the signifier-signified distinction that Augustine makes, or, like, the world, the scientific world as it really is, and the sort of, like, mystery of, or the obfuscating power of language.

321
00:34:57,860 --> 00:35:01,080
 And rhetoric is always sort of, like, you know, at the center of this.

322
00:35:01,600 --> 00:35:01,740
 Right.

323
00:35:01,740 --> 00:35:10,380
 And what I kind of realized in articulating this question and imagining responses and reading them is, it really does just seem like, yeah, there's no sublation.

324
00:35:10,380 --> 00:35:22,740
 It's just like, you know, Gorgias basically claims that language, there is no distinction that language produces all of these, like, all of these effects on one on others.

325
00:35:23,580 --> 00:35:26,240
 Plato's like, this is mere semblance, it's terrible.

326
00:35:27,240 --> 00:35:36,260
 Plato, Augustine, and Bacon are all like, you know, this is pure semblance, and either you can use it to reveal the truth, or you can use it to obscure it.

327
00:35:36,400 --> 00:35:39,740
 But that dichotomy, there's, like, there's no sublation between them.

328
00:35:40,920 --> 00:35:41,760
 There's no sublation.

329
00:35:41,980 --> 00:35:46,580
 But that's where it's cool when on Hegel, this is paragraph 47, and it speaks to that perfectly.

330
00:35:46,800 --> 00:35:51,260
 Like, this, I mean, I swear to God, this is a sentence out of being in time.

331
00:35:51,680 --> 00:35:53,840
 Like, I mean, I think it might actually be.

332
00:35:54,560 --> 00:36:04,040
 Appearance is the arising and passing away that does not itself arise and pass away, but is in and of itself and constitutes the actuality and the movement and the life of truth.

333
00:36:04,580 --> 00:36:04,960
 Right?

334
00:36:05,960 --> 00:36:10,680
 I mean, that, you know, that's an aufhebung from those kinds of positions, you know?

335
00:36:10,680 --> 00:36:10,880
 Right.

336
00:36:11,060 --> 00:36:19,080
 But appearance is the arising and passing away that constitutes the actuality and the movement and the life of truth.

337
00:36:19,780 --> 00:36:20,040
 Right?

338
00:36:20,160 --> 00:36:22,560
 Like, that's, truth is appearance.

339
00:36:22,880 --> 00:36:23,880
 I mean, that's the thesis.

340
00:36:24,200 --> 00:36:24,380
 Yeah.

341
00:36:24,560 --> 00:36:25,400
 That's a nice, concise little...

342
00:36:25,400 --> 00:36:31,200
 It is, after all, the phenomenology of spirit.

343
00:36:31,380 --> 00:36:32,740
 I mean, that's what it is.

344
00:36:33,160 --> 00:36:39,740
 I mean, there's another good, yeah, there's another good little, I'm not getting it exactly right, but it's like, the only thing behind, it's a Hegel quote,

345
00:36:39,800 --> 00:36:45,900
 the only thing behind appearances are what we put there, or like, you know, so it's like, it is a phenomenology.

346
00:36:45,960 --> 00:36:50,920
 And I feel like that's something that people also forget when we read this.

347
00:36:51,100 --> 00:37:00,480
 It's like, I mean, he makes, he's also written A Philosophy of Nature, so don't get me wrong, he's expanded beyond the simple phenomenology of spirit.

348
00:37:00,480 --> 00:37:11,400
 But all of this is, at a base level, incorporating the movement of subjectivity into various discourses that have suppressed that, you know?

349
00:37:11,640 --> 00:37:19,820
 But that's where, like, you know, if you tell the story that Nathaniel just told, it's like, it's fucking 2,000 years for one goddamn mouth hay bong.

350
00:37:20,240 --> 00:37:22,000
 Like, one, you know?

351
00:37:22,180 --> 00:37:29,360
 It's like, we've got semblance or appearance, and we've got, you know, and rhetoric, or we've got, you know, over here, truth, knowledge, philosophy.

352
00:37:29,680 --> 00:37:36,420
 And it took motherfucking 1,800 years to say, hey, maybe we don't have to choose.

353
00:37:36,980 --> 00:37:38,160
 Right, right.

354
00:37:38,660 --> 00:37:43,200
 Now, again, still, I would say, it's still the movement of truth.

355
00:37:43,400 --> 00:37:53,740
 Like, why does it have to be, I mean, like, my response to this would be, I mean, why does the arising and passing away that is appearance have to constitute the movement of truth?

356
00:37:53,740 --> 00:38:01,180
 Like, why, the payoff is always going to be on the side of truth, even when its content is now the realm of appearance.

357
00:38:01,420 --> 00:38:05,780
 But still, you're still playing the same kind of, the truth game, right?

358
00:38:05,880 --> 00:38:13,860
 It's just that now truth is mobile and not propositional, as opposed to just saying, it's just mobile and, you know, it's just mobile.

359
00:38:14,260 --> 00:38:19,220
 You know, there's, and I would be, well, I mean, my inclination is much more for coding that way.

360
00:38:19,280 --> 00:38:24,680
 It's like, well, look, truth is clearly propositional because that's how it's been taken for the most part.

361
00:38:25,020 --> 00:38:31,460
 Right, like, for the most, in other words, it's a rhetorical way of saying, truth is not some God term just handed down.

362
00:38:31,580 --> 00:38:33,380
 Truth is how people use it.

363
00:38:33,420 --> 00:38:36,280
 And how people have used it is in that propositional sense.

364
00:38:36,460 --> 00:38:40,780
 So, rather than fighting against that propositional sense, just say, like, you know.

365
00:38:41,420 --> 00:38:41,720
 Right.

366
00:38:42,460 --> 00:38:42,740
 Yeah.

